<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO; COUNCIL CANDIDATE FIELD DROPS TO 
NINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF BEAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A downtown businessman has pulled out of the race for City Council. 
</P>
<P>
 Tim Holsten, owner of the Vaquero West Mercantile, has decided not to seek a 
council seat in the Nov. 8 election so that he concentrate time on his business 
and his family, according to one of his daughters. 
</P>
<P>
 Holsten could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
 Holsten's decision to quit the campaign leaves nine candidates vying for three 
seats. 
</P>
<P>
 Gil Jones is the only council incumbent seeking reelection. Councilmen Gary L. 
Hausdorfer and Jeff Vasquez have decided not to run again. 
</P>
<P>
 The other candidates are: Serge Kohan, a salesman; Philipe Delgado Jr., a 
business owner and consultant; John Greiner, a human resource executive and 
Planning Commission chairman; Wyatt Hart, a retired Orange County Sheriff's 
Department captain and current Planning Commission member; Mario Pina, a postal 
carrier; David Swerdlin, a photographer and business owner, Steven M. Dallas, a 
radiation therapist, and Carlos Negrete, an attorney. JEFF BEAN 
